Neck 

 

Review the cervical vertebrae. Identify the spinous process, transverse foramen. What shape is the vertebral canal Which vertebrae are not pierced by the vertebral arteries? Review the unique structures of atlas and axis.  

 

The vertebral canal is the space in the vertebral column through which the spinal cord passes. It is essentially circular-oval, with a slightly increased diameter laterally. The vertebral arteries enter the transverse foramen of C6 and progress upward (through past C1). Vertebrae below C6 are not pierced by the vertebral arteries. 

 

The atlas (C1) and axis (C2) are both quite unique. C1 has no spinous process, and is capable of rotation through the pivot joint at the facet for the dens on C1. C1 also has specialised lateral masses for articulating with the occipital condyles of the skull.  

 

C2 is unique as it has the part known as "dens" for C1 lateral rotation.  

 

Identify the hyoid bone. Examine the greater and lesser horns.  

 

 

Identify the anterior triangle of the neck. What lies in this triangle? Which muscle separates the anterior and posterior triangles of the neck? 

 

 

Infrahyoid muscles 

 

 

 

The anterior triangle of the neck contains four suprahyoid muscles (stylohyoid, digastric, mylohyoid and geniohyoid) and four infrahyoid muscles (omohyoid, sternohyoid, thyrohyoid and sternothyroid). The sternocleidomastoid separates anterior from posterior triangle.  

 

The anterior triangle of the neck is split into four further triangles: the carotid triangle, the submandibular triangle, the submental triangle and the muscular triangle.  

 

 

 

Identify muscles, nerves, arteries and veins of this region. Ensure you can diagram this. What lies within the carotid sheath? 

Important arteries of the anterior neck include the common carotid and branches of the thyrocervical trunk. Important veins include the internal and external jugular veins. The carotid sheath contains the carotid artery, internal jugular and vagus nerve.  

 

Nerves 

 

 

Identify muscles, nerves, arteries and veins of the posterior triangle of the neck. 

Important arteries of the posterior neck include the vertebral artery (goes through spinous processes) and posterior to this, the deep cervical artery. Important veins include the vertebral vein (goes through spinous process of C7) end deep cervical vein.  

 

Identify the posterior triangle of the neck. What lies in this triangle? Can you identify the brachial plexus? Between which muscles does the brachial plexus emerge? 

The posterior triangle of the neck is split into the occipital triangle and the subclavian triangle: 

 

Brachial plexus 

The brachial plexus is a network of sensory and motor fibers innervating the upper limb and pectoral girdle. It lies between the pectoralis minor and the subscapularis muscle.

Thyroid 

 

Identify the two lobes of the thyroid and the connecting isthmus. Identify the arterial supply and venous return. Identify the pretracheal fascia and the parathyroid glands. 

 

Note that in around 40% of people a pyramidal lobe extends from the isthmus of the thyroid. 

 

The inferior thyroid arteries (left and right) arise from the thyrocervical trunks, which arise from the subclavian arteries. The superior and middle thyroid veins drain into the internal jugular, whilst the inferior thyroid vein drains into the brachiocephalic vein.  

 

The pre-tracheal fascia attaches the thyroid gland to the trachea and larynx, and this causes the thyroid to ascend on swallowing.  

 

The parathyroid glands are 4 pea-shaped structures on the back of the thyroid.
